children.subject: Hi Anon Comp, how much coding is 186, and if possible, could you also clarify the semester you took 186? From what I've gleaned, the statements about 186 are widely different. Some saying it's only 12 hours work each week, and some saying even heavier than 61C (which I input in like 25 hours each week) But they were from different semesters. What's your opinion on 186 workload, especially for semester spring 2021. (seems like W186 and 186 vary a lot?)

<md>I took it fall 2019 - since the class only has projects/vitamins and doesn't have homeworks/labs, i think the workload is very much coding-heavy. To my understanding, the projects are kept the same between w186 and 186 so that shouldn't cause a large variance. I heard that the course's projects were made harder prior to fall 19, so at least when i took it the class had a reputation for being an "easy" class based on prior offerings, but the workload is definitely substantial and has remained ~consistent after that point</md>
<md>the first project is very light, the second project is relatively light, but the 3rd-5th projects are all pretty heavy with 2-3 parts each</md>

i think it's pretty heavy but probably manageable. curious to hear other opinions, but i feel like 162 + 161 + data100 might be a more balanced schedule since 162 and 186 are both very much project heavy classes, and i feel like 161's project workload is less than 186's.

history.content: I did this exact workload a year ago (+1 unit decal since I'm LS and need 13 units) and did well but was a struggle to balance everything. 162 and 186 are both a LOT of coding. If you feel confident as a coder you'll be fine but otherwise be careful

Would this be a bad idea in terms of workload? The only other upper divs possibly being offered next semester that I'm interested in are 161 and 188, so would swapping 186/100 with one of these be better? I'm pretty set on taking 162 and I'm a transfer with only 2 semesters left to finish so I kinda need to take 3 technicals.
history.subject: CS 162 + 186 + data100
